  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most countries around the world, including China. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money appear legitimate by passing it through a series of transactions or businesses. This activity undermines the integrity of financial systems, fosters criminal behavior, and harms national security and economic stability.\n\nIn China, money laundering is explicitly prohibited under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China**, which was enacted to prevent and combat money laundering activities. The law requires financial institutions and specific non-financial entities to establish anti-money laundering (AML) measures, such as customer due diligence, record-keeping, and reporting suspicious transactions to authorities. Violators can face severe penalties, including fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment.\n\nChina actively participates in international efforts to combat money laundering and collaborates with global organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** to strengthen its AML frameworks and enforcement. Upholding the rule of law and combating financial crimes are essential components of China's commitment to maintaining a fair and secure financial environment.",
